AP SOSC S1 Selected Topics in Health and Society
  3115  3.00 A  EN ONLN  01  S20M01 
T11:30170Keele  
R11:30170Keele  
Blacker Sarah AP SOSC 3115 3.00 A S1: Special Topics: Indigenous Health and Food Sovereignty Practices This course examines a range of contemporary Indigenous Food Sovereignty practices designed to counter the health inequities that disproportionately affect Indigenous communities in settler colonial Canada. Through a focus on resurgence, students will explore Indigenous health and Food Sovereignty practices in relation to the following topics: interdependence and co-creation, nutritional colonialism and decolonizing food, environmental contamination and food security, climate adaptation, mental health, community stewardship, ecosystem health, inter-generational knowledge transfer, and land-based education. The course will follow a seminar format in which student preparation, presentation, participation, and discussion are key requirements for learning. Course Outline

AP SOSC OI State of the Art in Law & Society (Study Away)
  4371  3.00 A  EN FDEX  01  A48P01 
T11:30170KeeleVH 1152
W11:30170KeeleVH 1152
Amelie Barras Quebec appears to tackle questions related to religious diversity differently than other provinces in Canada. Why is that? What role does the Catholic heritage of the province play in understanding these differences? Why does this province feel the need to legislate on the place of religion in its society, and on secularism? What are the consequences of those legislations, especially for religious minorities? This seminar seeks to answer these questions and others by examining the evolution of religion, law and politics in Quebec. The provinces political history and contemporary debates on religion and secularism, as well as sites of worship and pilgrimages, are considered within the socio-cultural contexts that produced them. The course combines in-class seminar sessions, and field visits to a range of sites in Montréal, Quebec City and Sainte-Anne-de-Beaupré. Course Outline
